Taking the above analysis together, we have the following key findings: Time trends in BMI: Mean BMI of adults in Scotland was generally stable between 2008 and 2012, showing no significant trend of increase or decrease. The average value of each year was about 27.8, and the difference was not statistically significant. Age differences: BMI increased significantly with age. The average BMI was lowest (about 24.9) in the young group (16-24 years old), and reached the highest (about 28.8) in the middle age to pre-retirement group (45-64 years old), and it decreased slightly in the elderly group. Age is an important factor affecting BMI. Gender differences: The mean BMI of men and women were very close and the difference was not statistically significant. However, the proportion of overweight in men was higher than that in women, suggesting that men may be more worthy of attention in the definition of overweight. Differences in employment status: There were significant differences in BMI among the different employed groups. Students (students) had the lowest mean BMI, while retirees and those unable to work due to illness/disability had the highest mean BMI. Work status may reflect lifestyle differences that influence body weight. Differences in dietary habits: The average BMI of those who met the target of vegetable intake was slightly lower than that of those who did not meet the target, which was statistically significant. This suggests that good vegetable intake habits may contribute to the maintenance of lower body weight. The association between fruit consumption and BMI was not obvious, and even slightly higher in those who met the target than in those who did not meet the target, indicating that fruit consumption alone has a limited effect on BMI and may need to be considered in combination with overall dietary patterns. Discussion of Results: This study analysed trends in BMI and influencing factors between 2008 and 2012 using data from the Scottish Health Survey. Confidence in the results is high because the sample size is large and the data are derived from authoritative health surveys. The analysis revealed that overweight was a serious problem in Scottish adults in those years (average BMI over 25), with no significant improvement. This implies challenges for public health policy: sustained obesity interventions are needed, as natural trends do not decline on their own. The significant effects of age and employment status suggested that middle-aged people and retired/non-working people were high-risk groups, probably due to the decline of metabolism in midlife, life stress and decreased activity after retirement. These groups should be the focus of health policy interventions, such as providing exercise and nutrition guidance in the community. Regarding diet, the data support strategies to promote vegetable consumption for weight control; However, emphasizing fruit intake alone may not be sufficient to affect BMI, and an overall balanced nutritional strategy is needed. Future research directions and improvements: The analysis was extended to years after 2012 to examine trends in BMI over the last decade to assess the latest trends in the obesity problem. Additional variables, such as physical exercise frequency, total caloric intake, income level, and smoking and drinking, were introduced to construct more comprehensive regression models to account for the variation in BMI. Longitudinal data were considered to track changes in BMI over time in the same batch of individuals to distinguish between group and individual effects. It may be more relevant for policy to analyze the changes in the proportion and influencing factors of different BMI categories (such as normal, overweight, and obesity) than to only analyze the average value. To improve the accuracy of fruit and vegetable intake data, or subdivide different diet quality indicators to further explore the causal relationship between diet and BMI.
